title: For Sale/Trade:  Two - Mossberg (Howa) 3000 - 18.5" Police/Defense
postcontent:
I have for sale two Mossberg 3000s, these are from the late 1980s and were built originally for Smith and Wesson and later Mossberg by Howa Arms in Japan. These guns are essentially metric sized clones of Remington 870s, but with heavy duty lifters that won't allow shell-double feeds that 870s can have. 

One gun has sling-swivel forend cap and I installed a Magpul 870 stock on it (fits very well). Has Speedfeed forend, the Speedfeed stock that was on the gun, comes with it (it just didn't fit me). The other gun is virtually identical, except it has a standard forend cap and has Speedfeed stock installed. Guns show handling wear requisite with former police/security guns (plenty of rack wear, but limited shooting wear). Both guns have flat oversized safeties installed - I wish I could find a safety like this for an 870, they are perfect. I have fired both guns with bird, buck, and slugs the guns shoot excellent and are very smooth, as smooth as any worn-in 870. 

In the end I am selling these, because I am already invested in 870s and don't need shotguns outside of that platform. 

Asking $450 for BOTH. I prefer to sell BOTH guns not one individually. Since 3000s aren't made anymore you might as well have a spare. - If you don't want the Magpul stock on the bottom gun, I will reinstall the Speedfeed and sell you both guns for $400. 

Trades - I would consider trading both guns straight across for an excellent condition/new Remington 870 Police, preferably with wood furniture.

postcontent: To all interested buyers. Be very careful when it comes to buying this rifle. Lots of people are not aware that Ruger had made a 10/22 in the WMR and discontinued that rifle for a very good reason. The pressure for the round would cause the bolt to crack and cause failure of the rifle. They had conversion kits for the 10/22 Magnums to convert to .17hmr and stopped making them for the same reason and they have higher chamber pressure then the 22 magnum.  No matter what its still a 10/22 and nothing more. The vendors that sold the conversion kits at one even recommend not to convert your firearm due to known failures. Look it all up if you wont take my word for it. Your fingers, and eyes and life are worth more then some polished up turd.

title: For Sale:  Memorial Day, Honoring our Veterans
postcontent:
Memorial Day is a federal holiday for remembering the men and women who died while serving in the country's armed forces. The holiday, which is celebrated every year on the last Monday of May, was formerly known as Decoration Day and originated after the American Civil War to commemorate the Union and Confederate soldiers who died in the war. By the 20th century, Memorial Day had been extended to honor all Americans who have died while in the military service. It typically marks the start of the summer vacation season, while Labor Day marks its end. Remember those that have paid the ultimate price and never let their sacrifice be forgotten.

The price was their life for our freedoms honor their sacrifice.

postcontent: RARE- RARE- RARE- AVOID TICKET BY GAME WARDENS FOR LEAD 22LR BULLETS! ---------------------------------------------- Winchester .22 Long Rifle Lead-Free (26 grain TIN truncated hollow-point) Ammunition. Some States allows only non-lead ammunition when hunting. Until recently, thousands of California hunters had to shelve their .22 rifles & reach for other types of firearms to chase varmints in the Condor Zone. Winchester announced their .22 Long Rifle Lead Free Ammunition. This ammunition is described as a 26 grain tin hollow point bullet, zipping along at 1650fps. ------------------from internet------------- Another positive was the bullet energy when hitting a "hard target". I put that in quotes so you understand what I mean by hard target. Most of the lead free ammunition tends to be harder than lead. This tin ammunition is no different. However, when you hit a medium sized ground squirrel in the head or shoulder area, you will definitely hear a "crack" if the bullet hits any bone. Almost all of the hits shown in the video above passed completely through the ground squirrel. This was the case even when they were hit in the head. This was true when I first shot this ammunition back in March. I had to dispatch a skunk at my buddy's house up in the high desert. The skunk had an issue, as it walked up to the house in the middle of the day, bent on getting to the front porch, even with us using a hose and yelling to try and turn it. However, once the hose turned him back away from the house, my buddy asked me to dispatch it. I dropped it immediately with a shot to the shoulder at about 25 yards. It did not have a chance to spray and the bullet did not exit. It was very odd for the skunk to be so aggressive in the middle of the day, but the .22 took care of it. My final thoughts on the Winchester .22 Long Rifle Lead Free Ammunition is this. This is the only rimfire ammunition manufacturers to produce lead free. Price is for 1 box of 50, sealed sent to you with tracking number. Just so you know the California Fine for Leaded bullets including 22 is over $500 in fees & court costs per hunter per Ticket. Can be several tickets per day if you don't remove the ammo and firearm from the hunting group or hunter! -------------------------------------------- Tip without legal advice! With one box you qualify for "NON-LEAD" 22LR ammo. Keep the box with your all the time. Once you use up the TIN ammo, you may want to put lead Winchester 22LR in the plastic container just as insurance! I'm not suggesting this, you as an adult could be "lying" to law enforcement, but most of the time they look at the box, not test the bullet...
